<br>
Some key arguments:<br>
<br>
Nuclear energy does not emit greenhouse gases.  Its byproducts can be reprocessed and easily stored.  Most people in the scientific community believe Yucca Mountain will provide more than adequate housing for nuclear waste.<br>
<br>
Solar PV cells create a lot of pollution during their construction.  They take up a lot of space, can only be used in primarily sunny areas, and need a backup source such as natural gas to get through cloudy days and nights.  They are also quite expensive and according to Dept of Energy stats would significantly raise electricity costs.<br>
<br>
Wind power mills cause are a significant threat to birds and will probably lead to the extinction of many endagered species of birds.  Already, there have been many casualties and as wind generation increases, these will only increase.<br>
<br>
Name one major nuclear accident in the US in the past two decades?  How many people has nuclear energy killed?  Who are these people?  I want names, addresses, and names of physicians who have established their maledies are a direct cause of nuclear energy.<br>
<br>
No ill health effects have been observed for any radiation dose less than 65 times natural background.  These are from studies of the Hiroshima and Nagasaki bombings.  Although this does not prove there are NO ill health effects, most of the scientific community agrees they are minimal at best.<br>
<br>
There is even some evidence to say low levels of radiation can actually be beneficial to health.  In a study of dock workers of those who handled nuclear material and those who did not, the group that did were significantly healthier, lived longer, than those who did not.  This is an area of ongoing medical research and is starting to show some interesting results.<br>
<br>
Nuclear energy can be used to efficiently create hydrogen which can be used as a clean alternate fuel source for automobiles.<br>
<br>
Chernobyl was caused by an unstable design using a graphite moderator.  A moderator slows down neutrons so they can bind to U-235 nuclei easier and induce fission.  Without a moderator, the fission process stops.  In the US we use water which can drain away stopping the reaction, the Soviet reactor used graphite which heated up and exploded.  It is impossible for this disaster to occur in the US because of the different moderator.<br>
<br>
As bad as Chernobyl was, stress and the actions taken by the governments have actually caused more harm than the accident itself.  According to the UN, the only increased rates in cancer above background are several thousand cases of juvenile thyroid cancer.  These could have been easily prevented had the Soviet government placed restrictions on drinking milk and distributed Potassium Iodide tablets.  The ill effects of Chernobyl are due to bad decision making and bad government.<br>
<br>
These are a few arguments.  I hope they are useful. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mauk2>Mauk2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 192<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/3/03 11:07 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=678.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/3.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Arguement help</span><hr size=1> Nuclaeon covered the large majority of the &quot;common sense and facts&quot; arguments.  But there's a few more to toss out there.<br>
<br>
Coal is the largest source of electricity in the world today.  Nuclear and Hydro are the next two largest sources.  Coal is incredibly dirty, releasing billions of pounds of particulates and oxides into the air every year, just in the USA.  Part of those particulates released are uranium.  Several thousand pounds of uranium is released into the air every day by coal plants.<br>
<br>
Mining coal causes thousands of deaths every year from Black Lung and mining accidents.  If nuclear power was this lethal you'd never hear the end of it.  Why don't you ever hear about deaths from coal?  Could it be the greenies are hypocrits?<br>
<br>
Now, the two most likely sources to replace coal are nuclear and hydro.  Hydro is a finite resource, once you have developed  all the rivers, you're done.  Plus, building dams is not exactly environmentally benign.<br>
<br>
Nuclear is safer than either coal or hydro, by a large margin.  It is cleaner than coal by orders of magnitude, and is about the same as hydro if you leave off the environmental damage a dam causes.  <br>
<br>
Nuclear power plants can readily be built on the sites of old coal plants.  There is no way the nuclear plant is going to make the site any dirtier, and the amount of pollution is reduced drastically.<br>
<br>
Some greenies claim that there is only a 30 year supply od uranium.  This is false, we have enough uranium to supply all our electricity needs for over 60 years, even displacing coal.  We just need to recycle our fuel rods and recover the unused uranium in them.  If we switch to thorium as a nuclear fuel source, we have enough to last us for literally thousands of years.<br>
<br>
Some greenies claim that mining uranium creates more carbon release than is saved by making electricity with it.  This is completely false, uranium is incredibly energy dense and mining it is no harder or dirtier than mining copper or gold.  Plus, if we use reactors to make hydrogen we can reduce the carbon used to mine it to zero if we so desire.<br>
<br>
Last, for greenies who are completely emotional and who cannot be reasoned with any other way, just smack them with this oldie but goodie:  More people have died in Ted Kennedy's car than died in the Three Mile Island accident.<br>
<br>
Very cruel.  <br>
<br>
But true.<br>
