The power supply he likes the most is taking H2 out of the seas and oceans and using it to power cars and stuff as the main source, with geothermal, solar and the other 'clean' power sources as augmentation. I know modern reactors create H2O so we can extract H2 from there.  What are some other things that are bad with taking H2 out of the sea? <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=echuschasma@nuclearspace>echus chasma</A> at: 1/3/03 5:16:47 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=johnfraz>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_yingyang.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orion Commander</span><br>  Posts: 308<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/3/03 6:54 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=678.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://lneilsmith.com/tools/littlelogo.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/3.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Arguement help</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; What are some other things that are bad with<br>
taking H2 out of the sea?</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
More energy put into claiming the H2 from seawater than you get out of the H2 you extract. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Vastly</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> more.<br>
<br>
Very poor plan, or poor arguments from your friend. Major hole in his plan. That energy must come from somewhere, and geothermal &amp; hydro are localised, and frequently nowhere near where it's needed (industry &amp; habitation).<br>
Difficulty in storing &amp; transporting the H2 to the end user. (more a problem with the infrastructure lagging bahind. There are ways to use &amp; store H2, but they're not widespread)<br>
<br>
 Look also into breeders. Most of what we call &quot;radioactive waste' is spent fuel. Breeders use that to produce more energy than was produced making the spent fuel. The political problem with breeders is that the fuel comes out of them in a form which is rich in Pu 239, and that's readily made into weapons. Proliferation of weapons is the sole political reason we aren't using breeders today, and thereby taking care of the waste.<br>
 Note that now there are plans to burn up Pu as MOX fuel, to run it through yet another fuel cycle.<br>
<br>
The only problems with nuclear is that we aren't using it sanely. Full fuel cycle, and then bury it.<br>
Either Yucca Mt, or I like geological subduction zones even better. Encase waste in concrete, and bury it where the Earth's crust will carry it down into the magma below.<br>
<br>
Of course if you use the Pu in nuclear pulse rockets in space, then we really get good use out of it, and get rid of it finally! <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 637<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/4/03 1:54 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=678.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/3.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Arguement help</span><hr size=1> I agree with John Fraz, hydrogen isn't a powersource in itself since it doesn't exist in a free state.  If we produce hydrogen using coal burning plants it could actually make things worse.  I've heard from a few other people who think hydrogen is some kind of alternative to say nuclear or windmills, but they don't understand that it takes more energy to produce a given quantity of hydrogen than the H itself can produce.  Right now the best bet is nuclear fission plants being used to produce hydrogen.  That would give us both clean <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>and</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> abundant energy. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A> at: 1/4/03 1:57:11 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=echuschasma@nuclearspace>echus chasma</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 9<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/5/03 3:00 pm)</font><br