At least I've heard this seriously proposed by people who flunked H.S. science and think the government has agents following them and sabotaging their ISP and websites because of their dangerous knowledge...<br>
<br>
(I actually like electric cars. 90% of the driving we do could be done perfectly well by cars with low range, low power, and small size. Of course, some hybrids and even fully electric cars today don't have low range or power... I particularly like solar cells on the roofs of cars to drive air conditioners! -thanks to Spider Robinson, there)<br>
<br>
 Long term, the best solution for the planetary civilization is some version of SPS. Use beamed power to produce H2, react it with atmospheric CO2 to make readily used CH4 (methane). Remove CO2 from the atmospheric balance, and the only net addition to the biosphere is waste heat, which is also compensated for -along with atmospheric pollutants- by removing Earth-based heavy industry to space.<br>
And <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>that</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is the final nail in the coffin of soft decentralised technology; <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>removing heavy industry from the face of the planet</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->!<br>
Variously estimated that by 2050 we'll have 13+ billion people. Birth rates in the developed nations is at or near zero already, and the only way to bring the rest of them to ZPG (short of genocidal global atrocity warfare) is to raise their standards of living to match the richest of today. How else to support 15 billion people in better standards of living than today if not going to space for the dirty work of producing energy &amp; materials?<br>
Ask any &quot;greenie&quot; what they think of that? What about 500 years ahead -where might we be? Any good reason besides utopian dreaming or doomsday theorising that we shouldn't provide for the possibility of hundreds of billions of people and an Earth terraformed back into the wilderness it was 5K or 10K years ago?<br>
<br>
 Eventually, our use of nuclear power today (instead of turning off the electric grids) is to remove most nuclear power stations, to be replaced with SPS rectennae with absolutely no pollution of this, the only biosphere we know of.<br>
Use Pu from breeders (and warheads) in nuke pulse rockets to plant seed factories at NEAs, and build space factories to build SPS.<br>
<br>
This is long term, of course, but within 20 years we could see the first operational SPS, showing that the idea of &quot;blasting off in your rocketships&quot; isn't just escapism and the &quot;Disposable Planet&quot; philosophy.<br>
 We want to think about the long term somewhere, don't we? Not just the next 10 or 50 years, but 500 or 5000 years.<br>
<br>
Of course in reality, in 20 years we'll be wondering if Bin Laden is dead of old age, and if the Afghani oil pipeline was worth the endless war on terrorism, and where did all the oil from the ANWR evaporate to, and &quot;why does it have to cost so much to drive my <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://slate.msn.com/Features/GodzillaSUV/page2.asp">5 ton SUV</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->?&quot; (I heard an estimate that if the worst SUVs were regulated to get 3mpg better mileage, we'd save more oil in 10 years than we'll ever get out of the ANWR...)<br>
 In 5000 years, primitive farmers will be wondering why they're getting sick as they pull their own plows through the desert soil of Yucca mountain.<br>
